      "text": "# Foundations of Computation: Binary and Number Representation\n\n## Introduction\n\nAt the absolute core of every digital system, regardless of its scale or complexity, lies the binary digit. This fundamental concept, often glossed over in higher-level programming discussions, is the primal language understood by all electronic computation. This article, serving as the inaugural entry in our \"Foundations of Computation\" mega-series, undertakes a rigorous deconstruction of binary representation, tracing its lineage from the immutable laws of physics and electrical engineering to its profound impact on the architecture and reliability of modern computing systems. Mastery of binary is not an academic nicety; it is an operational imperative for any engineer seeking to diagnose elusive system failures, craft performant code, design robust distributed architectures, and possess a truly profound understanding of the computational universe.\n\n## Intuition\n\nTo build an intuitive foundation for binary, we must first anchor ourselves in the physical reality of digital hardware. Consider the simplest, most fundamental circuit element: a switch. This switch has two distinct, stable states: *open* or *closed*. Similarly, within a semiconductor, a transistor is either *conducting* or *non-conducting*. On a data bus, an electrical signal exists at either a *high voltage* or a *low voltage*. These are not arbitrary choices; they are engineered for 
